(832, 'EX-666640', 'FB', '<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"color:#4472c4\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\">PRINCESS SHEKINAH INTERNATIONAL SCHOOL, IHIAGWA</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\">THIRD TERM EXAMINATION 2018/2019 SESSION</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>SUBJECT: ENGLISH STUDIES CLASS: YEAR 8 </strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>PAPER 3 TIME: 60 MINUTES</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>SECTION A: READING COMPREHENSION (30 MINUTES)</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><em>Read the passage and answer the questions that follow.</em></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\">Gerrard &ndash; My Autobiography</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\">Still now I hate Sunday nights. Still! It&rsquo;s impossible to blank out the memory of getting ready for school, a ritual torture that ruined the final moments of a glorious weekend. According to the calendar most people use, a weekend lasts two days. Not at No. 10 Ironside by 6pm to be scrubbed, bathed and ready for school the next morning. We ran in at six and the uniform was there, on the ironing board, all pristine and pressed glaring at us. Just seeing the uniform made me sick. They resembled prison clothes after the freedom of the weekend. It was not that I hated school; I just loved my weekends roaming around Bluebell. Mum took school more seriously than Paul, my brother, and I ever did. A proud woman, she made sure our uniforms were absolutely spotless. She polished our shoes so hard you could see your grimacing face in them. Poor Mum! She had her work cut out. If I left the house with a clean uniform, it was guaranteed to come home dirty. the same with shoes. Scuffed and muddy. Every time. Mum went up the wall.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\">My journey through the Merseyside school system was straightforward and undistinguished. I looked on schools as fantastic playing fields with boring buildings attached. My first stop was St. Michael&rsquo;s, which became Huyton-with-Roby Church of England Primary. Though only a short walk from Ironside, Mum still insisted on driving me to St. Mick&rsquo;s and picking me up. I enjoyed the infants and junior school, just messing about. When I was naughty, the teachers made me stand by the wall, looking at the bricks for five minutes as punishment. I never bullied anyone. I never hurt anyone or swore. I was just cheeky and mischievous. My crimes were petty ones: answering back or going on muddy grass when we were told to stay on the yard. Usual kids&rsquo; stuff.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\">School held limited appeal. I sat in class, longing for playtime because there was always a match on in the playground. I loved dinner time because it lasted an hour, which meant a longer match. I abandoned hot dinners because they wasted precious minutes. Queuing for my meal, I&rsquo;d shout, &lsquo;Come on, there&rsquo;s a big game going on out there&rsquo;. Eventually, I asked my mother for packed lunches. &lsquo;You should be on hot dinners,&rsquo; she screamed, &lsquo;or come home if you don&rsquo;t like school food.&rsquo; We compromised on packed lunches: sandwich, bar of chocolate and drink. And some fruit. The fruit always came home untouched. Apples, bananas and Oranges weren&rsquo;t me. Butties (sandwiches) weren&rsquo;t me at that age. It would be bread off, meat out, quick bite, on with the game. &lsquo;Stevie, you haven&rsquo;t eaten your butty,&rsquo; Mum would say, &lsquo;you&rsquo;ve only eaten your chocolate.&rsquo; Mum didn&rsquo;t understand. Speed was vital at dinner time. I ate the packed lunch while playing or wolfed it down running back into class. Same with my tea. If there was a match going on outside Ironside, a game of chase, or my mates were waiting for me, I slipped my food in my pocket, sprinted out the door, threw the food to the neighbour&rsquo;s dog and raced on to the match. I returned home starving, picking at biscuits, crisps and chocolate.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\">Back at St Micks&rsquo;s, the teacher watched me scribbling away busily in my school book. Steam almost rose from my pencil as I wrote so furiously. The teachers must have thought I was focusing really hard on the lesson. I&rsquo;m sorry. I wasn&rsquo;t. Lessons were spent working out the teams for dinner time. In the back of my school book, I wrote down the names. When the bell for break rang, I dashed out to organize all the boys &ndash; and get the girls off the playground. &lsquo;You can watch,&rsquo; I do tell them generously, &lsquo;but that&rsquo;s the pitch and you can&rsquo;t go on it&rsquo;. The pitch was marked out with bags and tops for goals. They were right serious battles at St Mick&rsquo;s. Wembley Cup finals have been less intense. My face still bears the trace of a scar collected in the playground after I collided with a fence, tussling for the ball. Defeat was unthinkable.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><em><strong>Steven Gerrard</strong></em></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>Questions</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>Why did Steven Gerrard hate Sunday nights?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>Why does he say that to his mother a weekend was only a day and a half?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>What is meant by &lsquo;Mum went up to the wall&rsquo; and what did Steven do to make it </strong></span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:48px; text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>happen?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"4\">\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>What precious minutes do hot dinners waste?</strong></span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>Give the meaning of each of the following words as it is used in the passage:</strong></span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type:lower-alpha\">\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>grimacing</strong></span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>guaranteed</strong></span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>undistinguished</strong></span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>petty</strong></span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>compromised</strong></span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<ol start=\"6\">\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>Explain using your own words how Steven looked on the schools he attended.</strong></span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>Choose three details from the passage that show that Steven was fanatical about football and explain how the examples you have chosen show this.</strong></span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><br />\r\n&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>SECTION B: CONSTRUCTIVE WRITING (30 MINUTES)</strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><em>Answer both question 1 and 2. Your answer to each question should not be less than 200 words and not more than 250 words long. You are free to use the hints below each questions and/or any other ones you like.</em></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><em>Each question carries 30 marks.</em></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>Imagine that you are the head teacher at Steven&rsquo;s primary school. Using what you have learnt about him from the passage above, write his school report. You should write about three or more paragraphs</strong></span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\"><strong>Your own part of the town is in unsanitary condition with stinking gutters and garbage heaps here and there. Write a letter to the Chairman of your local government complaining of the situation, suggesting at least two things that can be done to improve the situation.</strong></span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:48px; text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\">You may use the suggested guidelines and/or any other ones you like.</span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<ol style=\"list-style-type:lower-alpha\">\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\">Introduction (if any)</span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\">The situation and the health dangers to which the area is exposed.</span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\">Suggestions on what can be done to improve it.</span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n	<li>\r\n	<p style=\"text-align:left\"><span style=\"font-family:Arial,serif\"><span style=\"font-size:medium\">Conclusion.</span></span></p>\r\n	</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n', '-', '-', '-', '-', '-', '', ''),
